  "opinion": "As a woman in my late 50s who’s spent decades working in fitness and community health, I’ve seen how science and fitness intersect in ways that often overlook the lived experiences of women. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about who gets to shape the questions we ask. Growing up, my parents had upper secondary education, which was typical for their time, but they never pushed me toward STEM fields. Instead, I found my passion through physical activity, which taught me about the body’s resilience and the importance of holistic health. Today, as a self-employed fitness trainer in Kansas City, I’ve noticed how many scientific studies on exercise or nutrition focus on male physiology, leaving women’s unique needs underrepresented. For example, research on heart health often uses male data as a default, which can lead to misdiagnosis in women. This gap isn’t accidental—it’s a result of historical biases that still linger. We absolutely should address it, but the way we do so matters. I believe the key is to integrate community-based, inclusive research that centers women’s voices from the start. In my work, I’ve started collaborating with local women’s health groups to co-design fitness programs that account for hormonal cycles and other factors often ignored in traditional science. It’s not about fixing science to fit gender—it’s about ensuring science reflects the diversity of human experience. As someone who’s curious and values practical, real-world solutions, I see this as both a moral and practical necessity. The time to act is now, not because it’s trendy, but because every woman deserves to be seen, heard, and valued in the scientific process.",
